<PageLayout
  title="Repository corticotropin (Acthar Gel): the original melanocortin drug — and a pricing cautionary tale"
  kicker="Approved drug"
  description="Acthar Gel is the oldest melanocortin drug — an injectable ACTH preparation approved in 1952, decades before the receptors were understood. It's also one of medicine's most notorious pricing stories: from under $40 a vial to nearly $39,000."
  updated="2026"
  about={[
    { name: 'Adrenocorticotropic hormone', type: 'MedicalEntity', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrenocorticotropic_hormone'] },
    { name: 'Corticotropin', type: 'Drug', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrenocorticotropic_hormone'] },
    { name: 'Infantile spasms', type: 'MedicalCondition', sameAs: ['https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epileptic_spasms'] },
  ]}
>
  <KeyTakeaways
    items={[
      'Acthar Gel (repository corticotropin) is a long-acting injectable preparation of ACTH, purified from pig pituitaries — the oldest melanocortin drug, approved in 1952.',
      'It is essentially the hormone ACTH, and therefore a pan-melanocortin agonist that activates all five receptors — the opposite of the selective, modern agents.',
      'It works both indirectly (stimulating the adrenal glands to release cortisol) and directly (melanocortin-receptor anti-inflammatory effects).',
      'It retains a clear role in infantile spasms and is used in acute MS flares, but its advantage over cheap generic steroids for many uses is disputed.',
      'Its price is infamous: from under $40 a vial to roughly $39,000 — about a 97,000% increase — making it a landmark case in US drug-pricing debate.',
    ]}
  />

  <p>
    Before there was a word for the "melanocortin system," there was Acthar Gel. Approved
    in <strong>1952</strong>, it is the oldest melanocortin drug by a wide margin — a
    reminder that this pathway was being used as medicine decades before anyone had cloned
    a melanocortin receptor. It is also, today, one of the most cautionary stories in the
    whole field: a crude old drug kept alive less by unique benefit than by an extraordinary
    price.<Cite n={3} />
  </p>

  <h2>What it actually is</h2>
  <p>
    Acthar Gel is <strong>repository corticotropin</strong> — a long-acting ("repository")
    gel preparation of <a href="/acth">ACTH</a>, the melanocortin hormone, purified from
    the pituitary glands of pigs.<Cite n={1} /> Because it is essentially ACTH, it is a
    <em>pan-melanocortin agonist</em>: it activates all five
    <a href="/receptors">melanocortin receptors</a>, the exact opposite of the careful
    receptor-selectivity that defines modern agents like
    <a href="/setmelanotide">setmelanotide</a> or <a href="/dersimelagon">dersimelagon</a>.
    It is the melanocortin drug as a blunt instrument.
  </p>

  <h2>How it works — two mechanisms, one debate</h2>
  <p>
    Acthar has two ways to act, and the balance between them is the source of decades of
    argument. The classic route is <strong>indirect</strong>: like natural ACTH, it drives
    the adrenal glands to release cortisol, so much of its effect is simply that of a
    steroid produced in the body.<Cite n={1} /> The more interesting claim is a
    <strong>direct</strong> one: by binding melanocortin receptors on immune cells, it may
    exert anti-inflammatory and immune-modulating effects beyond cortisol alone.<Cite n={2} />
    Whether that direct effect adds anything a cheap generic steroid cannot supply is exactly
    the question its critics raise.
  </p>

  <h2>What it treats</h2>
  <p>
    Acthar's clearest, least-disputed role is in <strong>infantile spasms</strong>, a
    severe infant epilepsy, where it is approved as monotherapy in children under two.<Cite n={1} />
    It is also approved for acute exacerbations of <strong>multiple sclerosis</strong> and
    carries a long list of older indications spanning rheumatic, kidney, and inflammatory
    diseases.<Cite n={1} /> Across much of that list, though, its benefit over inexpensive
    corticosteroids has never been convincingly shown — which is what makes its cost so hard
    to justify.
  </p>

  <h2>The price cautionary tale</h2>
  <p>
    For most of its life Acthar was cheap — under <strong>$40 a vial</strong> for decades.
    That changed when Questcor Pharmaceuticals acquired the rights in 2001 and began raising
    the price aggressively, past $31,000 a vial; Mallinckrodt then bought Questcor for
    $5.8 billion in 2014 and continued the climb to roughly <strong>$39,000 a vial</strong> —
    an increase on the order of <strong>97,000%</strong> from where it started.<Cite n={3} />
    Medicare spending on the drug ran into the billions, and the pricing drew investigative
    reporting and a congressional inquiry.<Cite n={3} /> For many patients a course of Acthar
    can exceed $100,000, against roughly $100 for a generic steroid treating the same
    condition.<Cite n={3} />
  </p>

  <h2>The honest bottom line</h2>
  <p>
    Acthar Gel occupies a strange place in the melanocortin story. Scientifically it is the
    ancestor — proof that this pathway was therapeutic long before it was understood — and it
    still helps children with infantile spasms. But it is also the field's clearest warning
    that an old, non-selective, incompletely-understood drug can persist less on merit than
    on price. The modern agents on this site are, in part, the answer to it: selective,
    tested, mechanistically defined. For the hormone Acthar is built from, see
    <a href="/acth">ACTH</a>; for the wider landscape, the
    <a href="/pipeline">melanocortin pipeline</a>.
  </p>

